snippet.textDisplay: Arguably the most devastating blow to any fighters ego, is that very first loss from a perfect record of professional wins. To be fair to Wilder, he would barely be human if he wasn't looking for bogus excuses to protect his ego from the uncomfortable truth, that he has come upon someone who can out box him & evade his only weapon. At the moment, he has bought into the hype of his invincibility via his knockout wins over 41 pro heavyweights, & cannot bring himself to countenance that he is only human. Humility will come in time. Ironically, now that his unbeaten record is over, the pressure is off him now, & he may be willing to listen to advice from wiser heads. Unfortunately, the other side of that coin is that fighters may not fear his right hand anymore now that Fury has exposed how to evade it & beat him.

snippet.textDisplay:
Roy is absolutely right . Fury has two major wins and the rest of his wins are questionable in quality . For Wilder it's the same thing .

I mean Fury and Wilder's first 20 fights individually were with either fighters that were not in their prime , sparring partners , or guys that weren't even sparring partner level ok . Fury beats Klitschko , so what .The Klitscko Bros weren't any good . The Heavy weight division when they reigned in that division was garbage . Klitchkos are punch once then grab fighters basically . Boring as hell . Even Fury said that . That's not greatness , that's survival fighting .

Fury won the titles then he got stripped for possibly being depressive and suicidal . I'm not buying it . Maybe Fury is one of those fighters that likes to be the underdog , have less pressure to perform , win the titles when not expected to , but not want to defend them once he has the titles and the pressure to defend them .That happens in Boxing sometimes . The chase is more exciting , than the catch to some fighters in boxing history . These fighters can just say they were on top of the mountain once , and thats fine with them .
